executable, CLI, MCP server, configurator binaries, etc. — are also
covered by this MIT license.


================================================================================
PART 2 — ENGINE BINARIES (proprietary, activation required)
================================================================================

The optical engine binaries (collectively, the "Engine"):

  * engine/LensHH.Core.dll       — managed optical-design engine
  * engine/win-x64/*.dll         — native ray-trace library (Windows x64)
  * engine/osx-arm64/*.dylib     — native ray-trace library (macOS arm64)
  * engine/linux-x64/*.so        — native ray-trace library (Linux x64)

are proprietary to Synapse Optics. They are NOT covered by the MIT
license in Part 1.

You may:

  * Run the Engine on any machine for which you hold a valid activation
    token — either an active free trial or a paid license.
  * Redistribute the Engine binaries UNMODIFIED, together with a
    LensHH-LT installer (the official one or a fork-built derivative),
    provided the activation gate is left in place. End users of any
    such installer must hold their own valid trial or license to run
    the Engine.

You may NOT:

  * Reverse-engineer, decompile, disassemble, or otherwise attempt to
    derive the source form of the Engine, except to the limited extent
    expressly permitted by applicable law that cannot be contractually
    waived.
  * Remove, bypass, modify, or interfere with the activation gate or
    any license-validation logic in the Engine.
  * Redistribute the Engine outside of an installer that preserves the
    activation gate.
  * Sublicense, rent, lease, or resell the Engine separately from a
    LensHH-LT installer.
  * Use the Engine to provide a hosted service whose primary value is
    Engine compute (i.e., a "lens design as a service" offering),
    without first obtaining a separate commercial agreement from
    Synapse Optics.

Activation:

  * A free 45-day trial is available — request a token at
    https://synapseoptics.com or from your distributor, then activate
    via Help → Start Free Trial in the LensHH-LT GUI.
  * A paid license binds one seat to one machine. To move it to a
    different machine, deactivate first via Help → Deactivate This
    Machine, then activate on the new machine.
  * Offline activation tokens are available for machines without
    internet access — contact support@synapseoptics.com with the
    machine ID shown under Help → License Status.


Forking and the open-core boundary
----------------------------------

The source-code half of LensHH-LT is fully MIT-licensed: you may fork
it, modify it, and redistribute the source and your derivative
binaries freely without asking permission.

A fork that redistributes the Synapse Optics Engine binaries
(`engine/LensHH.Core.dll` and the native libraries) does so under
Part 2 above — the activation gate must remain functional, and end
users still need their own trial or license. Alternatively, a fork
may strip the Engine and ship its own optical-engine implementation;
the public C# API surface is documented and stable enough for that
to be practical.

This Part 2 governs only the binaries listed above. No part of this
proprietary notice restricts the freedoms granted by the MIT license
in Part 1.
